<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Razor">

	<PropertyGroup>
		<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
		<ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
		<Nullable>enable</Nullable>
		<Version>1.1.3-rc.6</Version>
		<GeneratePackageOnBuild>True</GeneratePackageOnBuild>
		<GenerateDocumentationFile>true</GenerateDocumentationFile>
		<EmbedAllSources>true</EmbedAllSources>
		<DebugType>Embedded</DebugType>
		<Title>SpawnDev.RTC</Title>
		<Authors>LostBeard</Authors>
		<Description>Cross-platform WebRTC for .NET. Browser (Blazor WASM) and desktop from a single API. Data channels, audio, video, media streams, tracks, transceivers, ICE, DTLS, SCTP. Zero-copy JS types in WASM. Serverless signaling via WebTorrent tracker protocol. Powered by SpawnDev.BlazorJS (browser) and SipSorcery (desktop).</Description>
		<PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/LostBeard/SpawnDev.RTC</PackageProjectUrl>
		<PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>
		<PackageLicenseFile>LICENSE.txt</PackageLicenseFile>
		<PackageIcon>icon-128.png</PackageIcon>
		<RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/LostBeard/SpawnDev.RTC.git</RepositoryUrl>
		<RepositoryType>git</RepositoryType>
		<PackageTags>Blazor;BlazorWebAssembly;WebRTC;CrossPlatform;DataChannel;Video;Audio;MediaStream;ICE;DTLS;SCTP;SipSorcery;WebTorrent;P2P;RealTime</PackageTags>
		<PackageReleaseNotes>v1.1.3-rc.6: Fix a race in `PerfectNegotiator.HasNegotiated`. rc.5 set the flag after the `await sendDescription(...)` call, but a consumer awaiting that callback (e.g. a test TaskCompletionSource) resumes in the same synchronous step and observed `HasNegotiated=false`. rc.6 flips the flag right after `SetLocalDescription()` succeeds, before the send-await, so the flag is consistent by the time any awaiter observes the emitted description. v1.1.3-rc.5: New `SpawnDev.RTC.PerfectNegotiator` helper - W3C glare-free renegotiation pattern packaged as a drop-in class. Wraps an `IRTCPeerConnection` and two signaling callbacks (`sendDescription`, `sendCandidate`), auto-subscribes to `OnNegotiationNeeded` + `OnIceCandidate`, exposes `HandleRemoteDescriptionAsync` + `HandleRemoteCandidateAsync` for the app to call on incoming signaling messages. Implements the polite/impolite role assignment from the W3C spec (`https://w3c.github.io/webrtc-pc/#perfect-negotiation-example`): impolite side wins offer collisions, polite side rolls back its in-flight offer. With the helper wired up, subsequent `AddTrack`/`AddTransceiver`/`CreateDataChannel` from either peer triggers renegotiation automatically and concurrent renegotiations resolve without data loss. Works on both Browser (Blazor WASM) and Desktop (SipSorcery) platforms via the shared `IRTCPeerConnection` interface. 8 new unit tests cover construction, null-arg validation, idempotent disposal, and auto-offer-on-needsNegotiation. Closes the Plan Phase 7 "perfect negotiation state-machine helpers" item. v1.1.3-rc.4: `BrowserRTCSctpTransport` wires its typed properties through live JSRef reads instead of hardcoded defaults. Pre-rc.4 we returned `State="connected"`, `MaxMessageSize=262144`, `MaxChannels=65535` as stubs and the DTLS `Transport` getter was `null!` (TODO placeholder). rc.4 reads the actual `state`, `transport`, `maxMessageSize`, `maxChannels` properties from the native `RTCSctpTransport` via `JSRef.Get&lt;T&gt;()`, so callers now get the live browser-reported values (Chrome 262144 vs Firefox larger; Transport resolves to a live BrowserRTCDtlsTransport). No BlazorJS changes needed - the wrapper class already existed, we just weren't using its JSRef. v1.1.3-rc.2: Dep-bump to SpawnDev.SIPSorcery 10.0.5-rc.2 which exposes per-association SCTP burst tunables (`SctpAssociation.MaxBurst` + `SctpAssociation.BurstPeriodMilliseconds`). RFC 4960 §7.2.2 defaults (4 chunks / 50 ms) preserved for WAN. Consumers that know their link is loopback / LAN can raise MaxBurst (e.g. 32) via `DesktopRTCPeerConnection.NativeConnection.sctp.RTCSctpAssociation.MaxBurst = 32` to recover the throughput the RFC default was leaving on the table. Expected impact at MaxBurst=32 on sub-10ms RTT: ~8x end-to-end throughput improvement over rc.1. No SpawnDev.RTC source changes. v1.1.3-rc.1: Picks up SpawnDev.SIPSorcery 10.0.5-rc.1 which fixes the SctpDataSender lost-wakeup race (60x on zero-RTT benchmark; real-world still RTT-bound until MaxBurst tuning arrives in rc.2).

v1.1.2-rc.2: Proper fix for the SIPSorcery fork packaging - no more workarounds. The fork's PackageId is renamed from "SIPSorcery 10.0.4-pre" (which collided with upstream and couldn't be published) to "SpawnDev.SIPSorcery 10.0.4-local.1", published as a first-class nuget package. SpawnDev.RTC now declares a normal PackageReference to SpawnDev.SIPSorcery - no hidden bundling, no PrivateAssets tricks, no SuppressForkDep flag, no explicit transitive PackageRefs. Deletes 4 workarounds: SuppressForkDep property, conditional PrivateAssets, AddProjectReferencesToPackage target, manually-declared SIPSorcery transitive deps. Ships on the same ICE-gathering fix as rc.1 (RtcPeerConnectionRoomHandler waits for gathering before serializing SDP to the tracker - real reason text chat never worked through the signaling flow).

v1.1.2-rc.1: Fix RtcPeerConnectionRoomHandler serializing offer/answer SDPs before ICE gathering completes. The WebTorrent tracker wire protocol does not support trickle-ICE, so the full SDP with candidates must be in the announce payload. On Browser (and most Desktop stacks) CreateOffer/CreateAnswer return before gathering finishes, so peers received each other's SDPs with no candidates and could never establish a data channel. Handler now waits up to 5s for IceGatheringState == "complete" after SetLocalDescription and serializes pc.LocalDescription.Sdp (which has the candidates). Fixes the chat demo and any live TrackerSignalingClient consumer. Also: pack-time PrivateAssets condition so the nuspec suppresses the fork SIPSorcery dep for external consumers without breaking in-repo dev builds.

v1.1.1: Packaging fix - fork SIPSorcery.dll + SIPSorceryMedia.Abstractions.dll are now bundled inside lib/net10.0/ of this nupkg (ILGPU pattern: PrivateAssets="All" + AddProjectReferencesToPackage target). Previously the nuspec declared a dependency on SIPSorcery 10.0.4-pre which is our fork and not on nuget.org, breaking CI / GitHub Pages consumers who PackageReference SpawnDev.RTC. No code change from 1.1.0.

v1.1.0: New SpawnDev.RTC.Signaling namespace - WebTorrent-independent signaling abstraction. ISignalingClient / ISignalingRoomHandler interfaces, RoomKey helper (SHA-1 of raw UTF-8 room name, no normalization), TrackerSignalingClient (WebTorrent tracker wire protocol), RtcPeerConnectionRoomHandler (default room handler with PC pool). Legacy RTCTrackerClient removed - consumers migrate to TrackerSignalingClient. Pairs with SpawnDev.RTC.Server 1.0.0 for self-hosted signaling. Also: SipSorcery fork NetServices cctor guard for WASM + WaitForIceGatheringToComplete option on Desktop.</PackageReleaseNotes>
		<NoPackageAnalysis>true</NoPackageAnalysis>
		<EnableDefaultCompileItems>true</EnableDefaultCompileItems>
		<IsPackable>true</IsPackable>
		<LangVersion>latest</LangVersion>
		<AllowUnsafeBlocks>true</AllowUnsafeBlocks>
		<!-- Suppress missing XML doc warnings for now -->
		<NoWarn>$(NoWarn);CS1591</NoWarn>
	</PropertyGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
		<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Web" Version="10.0.2" />
		<PackageReference Include="SpawnDev.BlazorJS" Version="3.5.3" />
		<PackageReference Include="SpawnDev.BlazorJS.Cryptography" Version="3.2.0" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
		<InternalsVisibleTo Include="SpawnDev.RTC.Server" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<!-- SpawnDev.SIPSorcery is our fork of SIPSorcery (namespace + AssemblyName identical
	     to upstream for drop-in compatibility). Conditional wiring:
	       * In-repo builds where the submodule sibling exists: use ProjectReference for
	         hot-iteration. Transitive deps (BouncyCastle, Concentus, etc.) flow normally.
	       * External / standalone builds: use PackageReference so NuGet resolves the
	         fork package from the feed (local or nuget.org).
	     Standard .NET ecosystem conditional pattern (ASP.NET Core uses it). -->
	<ItemGroup Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\Src\sipsorcery\src\SIPSorcery\SIPSorcery.csproj')">
		<ProjectReference Include="..\Src\sipsorcery\src\SIPSorcery\SIPSorcery.csproj" />
	</ItemGroup>
	<ItemGroup Condition="!Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\Src\sipsorcery\src\SIPSorcery\SIPSorcery.csproj')">
		<PackageReference Include="SpawnDev.SIPSorcery" Version="10.0.5-rc.2" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<!-- SpawnDev.MultiMedia supplies cross-platform IAudioTrack / IVideoTrack abstractions
	     that Phase 4 wires into SipSorcery's RTP encoder on desktop. Same conditional pattern
	     as the SIPSorcery fork: sibling-repo ProjectReference when present (dev iteration),
	     otherwise PackageReference from the feed. -->
	<ItemGroup Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\..\..\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia.csproj')">
		<ProjectReference Include="..\..\..\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia.csproj" />
	</ItemGroup>
	<ItemGroup Condition="!Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\..\..\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia\SpawnDev.MultiMedia.csproj')">
		<PackageReference Include="SpawnDev.MultiMedia" Version="0.1.0-rc.1" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
		<None Include="Assets\icon-128.png" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
		<None Include="..\LICENSE.txt" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
		<None Include="..\README.md" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
		<None Include="wwwroot\icon-128.png" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
		<Content Remove="wwwroot\icon-128.png" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
		<SupportedPlatform Include="browser" />
		<SupportedPlatform Include="windows" />
		<SupportedPlatform Include="linux" />
		<SupportedPlatform Include="macos" />
	</ItemGroup>

	<ItemGroup>
	  <Folder Include="Browser\" />
	  <Folder Include="Desktop\" />
	</ItemGroup>

</Project>
